\begin_layout Section
Suggested routes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve the objective of generating functional racing tracks levels there
 are several constraints that needed to be considered so they ca be used
 in a racing game.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we will describe possible ways encountered to solve the
 creation of the racetrack and the decision process made toward the route
 that was taken.
 This is important as it is the base to define the data that would be collected
 and fed to out ML Agent as input.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Assembled pieces vs Bezier curve
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first decision to make was the way that the path creation would be handled,
 even if it was generated by a human.
 There were two routes explored for this Assembled pieces and Mesh generated
 from a bezier curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
assembled pieces
\series default
 pipeline proposes having several prefabs that can be put together with
 everything needed (mesh, the material with textures, the colliders, etc).
 This way we would have prefabs for all the possible directions, such as:
 forward, small turn, big turn, slope, etc.
 (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Assembled-pieces"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having 
\begin_inset Formula $4n$
\end_inset

 possible setups for each tile.
 For each piece we have four possible rotations in 
\begin_inset Formula $0Â°,90Â°,180Â°$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $270Â°$
\end_inset

 degrees.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The original idea for this (not implemented) process is for each one of
 the pieces to have a code from 1 to n.
 Leaving 0 for a part of the scene without any piece.
 And with the help of some cellular automata generate and fill a matrix
 that would help us to do some assembly of the tracks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem with this approach is that for it to be tried out easily, all
 the pieces would need to have a predetermined size to help assemble them
 with the help of a matrix.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename MLAgents_Assembledpieces.png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Assembled-pieces"

\end_inset

Assembled pieces
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
bezier curve
\series default
 is a better solution that allows more freedom for the track design and
 route.
 The bezier curve can be implemented with as little as with a list of Vector3's
 describing the control points positions that will form our curve.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Bezier-curve-tool"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 This way we can make sure that the track fully loops by connecting the
 last and the first control point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This process consists on generating a random set of points as Vector3 and
 allow them to be connected.
 With this bezier curve created, we can use a tool to extrapolate the mesh
 to make it visible and use it to apply a material and a collider to allow
 it to be usable as a Racing Track.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the process that seems to give a nicer result, so it was the one
 explored with our Generator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename MLAgents_BezierCurve.png
	lyxscale 50
	width 6cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Bezier-curve-tool"

\end_inset

Bezier curve tool.
 Consists of a series of control points positions described as Vector3 xyz
 floats.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
XYZ-space vs XZ-space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another decision to make was the use of the 3D space as there is the possibility
 to actually use the three axis XYZ for our control points positions.
 Creating the racing track in a XYZ-space is far more interesting as it
 can create more complex routes but at the same time it becomes harder to
 control properly (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1)-XYZ--space"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) as there are many more variables to consider as what qualifies as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

valid
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 racing track in the classification process.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The XZ-space is more simple, and is good enough for our objective as it
 can still be fully playable.
 The main specification to focus is the avoidance of overlapping sections
 in the racetrack path.
 The decision is to use just the XZ-space for the generation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename MLAgents_BezierCurveMesh.png
	lyxscale 40
	width 7cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
